üìò Security Concepts ‚Äì PG-DITISS (Aug 2025)
Session 2: Denial of Service, Buffer Overflow & Input Validation, Access Control
üîπ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. The primary goal of a Denial of Service (DoS) attack is to:
A. Steal data
B. Modify database
C. Make service unavailable
D. Gain admin access

2. Which security property is MOST affected by DoS attacks?
A. Confidentiality
B. Integrity
C. Availability
D. Authentication

3. Buffer overflow occurs when:
A. Input is encrypted
B. Input exceeds allocated memory
C. Firewall blocks traffic
D. Password is weak

4. Which programming language is MOST prone to buffer overflow?
A. Python
B. Java
C. C
D. PHP

5. Input validation mainly protects against:
A. Malware
B. Unauthorized input
C. Network attacks
D. Power failure

6. Access control defines:
A. How data is encrypted
B. Who can access what
C. How logs are stored
D. How packets flow

7. Which access control model assigns permissions to roles?
A. DAC
B. MAC
C. RBAC
D. ABAC

8. Which attack floods a server with excessive requests?
A. XSS
B. DoS
C. SQL Injection
D. CSRF

9. Improper input validation can lead to:
A. SQL Injection
B. XSS
C. Buffer Overflow
D. All of the above

10. Access control is enforced AFTER:
A. Authorization
B. Authentication
C. Encryption
D. Logging

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Difference between DoS and DDoS is:
A. Tool used
B. Number of attackers
C. Protocol used
D. Payload type

12. Which protocol is commonly abused in DoS attacks?
A. FTP
B. ICMP
C. SMTP
D. DNS

13. Buffer overflow mainly exploits which weakness?
A. CPU speed
B. Memory management
C. Encryption strength
D. Authentication logic

14. Stack-based buffer overflow allows attacker to:
A. Read logs
B. Execute arbitrary code
C. Capture packets
D. Bypass firewall

15. Input validation should be performed at:
A. Client side only
B. Server side only
C. Both client & server side
D. Database side only

16. Which is an example of improper access control?
A. HTTPS usage
B. Admin page accessible to normal user
C. Strong password
D. MFA enabled

17. Which access control model is MOST restrictive?
A. DAC
B. RBAC
C. MAC
D. ABAC

18. SYN Flood attack exploits:
A. UDP handshake
B. TCP three-way handshake
C. DNS resolution
D. ARP cache

19. Input validation failure is a root cause of:
A. DoS
B. Injection attacks
C. Network sniffing
D. Port scanning

20. Which mechanism helps mitigate DoS attacks?
A. Input validation
B. Rate limiting
C. Encryption
D. Hashing

üî∫ ADVANCED MCQs (10) ‚Äì CCEE TRICK ZONE
21. Which CIA principle is directly tested in DoS lab assignment?
A. Confidentiality
B. Integrity
C. Availability
D. Authentication

22. Why are buffer overflows less common in Java?
A. Java is slower
B. Automatic memory management
C. Encrypted memory
D. Uses firewall

23. Which payload may trigger buffer overflow?
A. Normal username
B. Very long string input
C. Encoded password
D. Encrypted token

24. Access control failure mainly leads to:
A. Service crash
B. Privilege escalation
C. Packet loss
D. DoS

25. Which attack combines availability loss with multiple sources?
A. DoS
B. DDoS
C. MITM
D. XSS

26. Input validation bypass in lab means attacker:
A. Crashes server
B. Executes malware
C. Gets unauthorized access
D. Changes firewall rules

27. Which access control model is rule-based and centrally enforced?
A. DAC
B. RBAC
C. MAC
D. ABAC

28. Why client-side validation alone is insecure?
A. Slower execution
B. Can be bypassed by attacker
C. Uses JavaScript
D. Needs browser support

29. Buffer overflow attacks can overwrite:
A. Heap metadata
B. Return address
C. Function pointers
D. All of the above

30. DoS attack success is measured by:
A. Data theft
B. System slowdown/unavailability
C. Password compromise
D. Privilege escalation

